d not feel like opening a raw JSON log or a giant\n   413\tchat transcript. It should feel like exploring the working history behind the\n   414\tpull request.\n   415\t\n   416\tGood session browsing behavior:\n   417\t\n   418\t- show related sessions as a small list with readable labels, agent/provider,\n   419\t  capture time, and relevance reason\n   420\t- show turns within a selected session as a compact timeline\n   421\t- group records into human request, assistant response, tool call, tool result,\n   422\t  and validation blocks\n   423\t- collapse noisy tool output by default\n   424\t- highlight commands that changed files, ran tests, failed, or produced useful\n   425\t  evidence\n   426\t- make related branches, reviews, changes, files, and validation attempts easy\n   427\t  to scan\n   428\t- let the user expand exact transcript records when they need evidence\n   429\t- preserve chronological order without forcing the user to read every record\n   430\t\n   431\tThe reviewer should be able to answer:\n   432\t\n   433\t- what did the human ask?\n   434\t- what did the agent claim it did?\n   435\t- what files or areas did it touch or inspect?\n   436\t- what commands/tools ran?\n   437\t- what validation passed, failed, or was skipped?\n   438\t- what decisions, doubts, or follow-ups appeared during the work?\n   439\t\n   440\tThe UI should support both broad scanning and exact drill-down. A reviewer\n   441\tshould be able to start at the PR overview, jump into a highlighted turn, expand\n   442\tthe relevant tool call or assistant claim, then return to the overview without\n   443\tlosing context.\n   444\t\n   445\tRaw transcript records should remain available, but they should be treated as an\n   446\tevidence drawer, not the primary browsing mode.\n   447\t\n   448\t## Ranking And Highlighting\n   449\t\n   450\tThe page should rank or highlight likely relevant turns. Relevance is a product\n   451\tdecision above `but-agentlog`.\n   452\t\n